N, Germany":"Wetterau, Hesse, Germany","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Anna","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[{"name":"Anne","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."]}]},{"name":"Barbara","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin, meaning ‘foreign woman’ (a feminine form of <i>barbarus</i> ‘foreign’, from Greek, referring originally to the unintelligible chatter of foreigners, which sounded to the Greek ear like no more than <i>bar-bar</i>).  St Barbara  has always been one of the most popular saints in the calendar, although there is some doubt whether she ever actually existed. According to legend, she was imprisoned in a tower and later murdered by her father, who was then struck down by a bolt of lightning. Accordingly, she is the patron of architects, stonemasons, and fortifications, and of firework makers, artillerymen, and gunpowder magazines."],"variants":[{"name":"Barbra","meanings":["From Latin, meaning ‘foreign woman’ (a feminine form of <i>barbarus</i> ‘foreign’, from Greek, referring originally to the unintelligible chatter of foreigners, which sounded to the Greek ear like no more than <i>bar-bar</i>).  St Barbara  has always been one of the most popular saints in the calendar, although there is some doubt whether she ever actually existed. According to legend, she was imprisoned in a tower and later murdered by her father, who was then struck down by a bolt of lightning. Accordingly, she is the patron of architects, stonemasons, and fortifications, and of firework makers, artillerymen, and gunpowder magazines."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Anna Barbara was born on 31 January 1683, in Germany. She had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with Wilhelm Conrad Repp. She died on 11 January 1725, in her hometown, at the age of 41."},"et":{"January 31, 1683–January 11, 1725":"31. jaanuar 1683–11. jaanuar 1725","1680–1719":"1680–1719","1711–Female":"1711–Surnud","1716–1786":"1716–1786","1718–1800":"1718–1800","1683–1725":"1683–1725","1800":"1800","1711":"1711","January 11, 1725":"11. jaanuar 1725","1786":"1786","1683":"1683","1719":"1719","1718":"1718","1680":"1680","January 31, 1683":"31. jaanuar 1683","1716":"1716","28 March 1716":"28. märts 1716","1725":"1725","Hesse, Wetteraukreis, Hessen, Allemagne Germany":"Saksamaa","Germany":"Saksamaa","Wetterau, HESSEN, Germany":"Wetterau, Hessen, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"January 31, 1683–January 11, 1725":"31. tammikuuta 1683–11. tammikuuta 1725","1680–1719":"1680–1719","1711–Female":"1711–Kuollut","1716–1786":"1716–1786","1718–1800":"1718–1800","1683–1725":"1683–1725","1800":"1800","1711":"1711","January 11, 1725":"11. tammikuuta 1725","1786":"1786","1683":"1683","1719":"1719","1718":"1718","1680":"1680","January 31, 1683":"31. tammikuuta 1683","1716":"1716","28 March 1716":"28. maaliskuuta 1716","1725":"1725","Hesse, Wetteraukreis, Hessen, Allemagne Germany":"Saksa","Germany":"Saksa","Wetterau, HESSEN, Germany":"Wetterau, Hessen, Saksa"},"fr":{"January 31, 1683–January 11, 1725":"31 janvier 1683–11 janvier 1725","1680–1719":"1680–1719","1711–Female":"1711–Décédée","1716–1786":"1716–1786","1718–1800":"1718–1800","1683–1725":"1683–1725","1800":"1800","1711":"1711","January 11, 1725":"11 janvier 1725","1786":"1786","1683":"1683","1719":"1719","1718":"1718","1680":"1680","January 31, 1683":"31 janvier 1683","1716":"1716","28 March 1716":"28 mars 1716","1725":"1725","Hesse, Wetteraukreis, Hessen, Al